-- Sub-Saharan African Stocks: Afribank, Air Mauritius and Ghana Bank Move
-- Vincent Nwanma
-- 2010-06-18T15:42:52Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-18/sub-saharan-african-stocks-afribank-air-mauritius-and-ghana-bank-move.html

          
          
             Mauritius’s  SEMDEX Index  rose 0.3
percent to 1,638.95, a fourth day of gains, at the close in Port
Louis.  
 Kenya’s  All-Share Index  rose for the first time in four
days, gaining less than 0.1 percent to 73.69 at the close in
Nairobi.  
 The  Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index  dropped 0.2
percent to 25,861.93 in Lagos, the first decline
since June 10.  
 Namibia’s  FTSE/Namibia Overall Index  was fell 5.96 points,
or 0.8 percent to 767.31, while the  Ghana Stock Exchange All-
Share Index  added 0.6 percent to 6,569.44 for a second day of
gains.  
 The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding South Africa. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  
 Afribank Plc  (AFRIBANK NL), a Nigerian lender bailed out by
the  Central Bank of Nigeria  last year, fell the most in three
days after reporting that its loss widened to 230.1 billion
naira ($1.52 billion) last year from 158.5 billion naira in
2008.  
 The stock dropped 8 kobo, or 3.9 percent, to 1.95 naira, in
Lagos, the commercial hub.  
 Air Mauritius Ltd.  (AML MP), the stated-owned carrier,
surged the most in a year after reporting its full-year loss
narrowed to 6.04 million euros ($7.5 million) in the 12 months
through March, from 85.4 million euros a year earlier.  
 The stock jumped 1.4 rupees, or 11 percent, to 13.9 rupees,
the biggest gain since June 17, 2009, according to Bloomberg
data.  
 “The results have exceeded market expectations,” Vikash
Tulsidas, managing director of Axys Stockbroking in Port Louis,
said in a phone interview. “The other good thing is that Air
Mauritius expects the same upward trend.  
 Continental Reinsurance Plc  (CONTINSU NL), a Nigerian
reinsurer, rose to its highest close in 11 days after announcing
first-quarter profit rose 57 percent to 385.4 million naira
($2.54 million).  
 The stock gained 5 kobo, or 4.4 percent, to 1.2 naira
 in Lagos.  
 Ghana Commercial Bank Ltd.  (GCB GN), Ghana’s biggest
lender, rose on expectations that a recent government bond sale
would be used to pay debt owed to the lender.  
 Ghana Commercial rose 18 pesewas, or 12 percent, to 1.65
cedis in the capital, Accra.  
 “More funds will be coming” to Ghana Commercial from the
proceeds of the bond sale, said Hilary Lomotey, a trader with
Renaissance Capital in Accra.  
 Kenya Airways Ltd.  (KNAL KN), sub-Saharan Africa’s third-
biggest carrier, fell to its lowest level in three months on
concern that the delayed delivery of new planes may cut revenue.
The stock fell 1 shilling, or 2.1 percent, to 47.25 shillings.  
